      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You can implement the `check_permission` function using a conditional statement based on the user's role and the resource's owner. Here's how you can do it:\n\n```python\ndef check_permission(user, resource, action):\n    if user.role == 'admin':\n        return True\n    if user.role == 'editor':\n        if user.user_id == resource.owner_id:\n            return True\n        return False\n    if user.role == 'viewer':\n        if user.user_id == resource.owner_id:\n            return True\n        if user.role == 'editor':\n            return True\n        return False\n```\nThis function checks the user's role first. If the user is an admin, they are granted permission to perform any action. If the user is an editor or viewer, they can perform actions based on whether they are the owner of the resource and their own. This implementation accurately reflects the roles' hierarchy in your problem.",
